      "requiredLevel": 5,
      "achievedLevel": 5,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/morrison-cou2-discretization-criteria",
      "rationale": "Systematic mesh refinement study conducted on five geometrically similar hexahedral meshes (0.8M, 2.1M, 5.4M, 13.8M, 35.2M cells). Grid Convergence Index (GCI) computed per Roache (1994) for NIH QoI: GCI_fine = 0.31%, GCI_medium = 1.14%. Asymptotic ratio confirms convergence in the asymptotic range (ratio = 1.02 ± 0.04). Production mesh (13.8M cells) selected; discretization uncertainty contribution to NIH is ±0.8% (95% CI). Dataset linked: morrison-mesh-convergence-dataset-v2."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 5,
      "achievedLevel": 5,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/morrison-cou2-test-conditions-criteria",
      "rationale": "Experimental test conditions are fully characterised and documented. Inlet flow rates measured with Coriolis mass flowmeter (±0.5% full scale, NIST-traceable calibration). Rotational speed monitored with optical tachometer (±5 RPM). Fluid temperature maintained at 37 ± 0.5 °C using recirculating bath; viscosity and density measured at each operating point. All five operating conditions (2.5 L/min at 3000 RPM through 6.0 L/min at 4500 RPM) replicated in triplicate. Environmental conditions (ambient pressure, humidity) logged throughout. Test protocol MCTC-2025-007 archived."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 5,
      "achievedLevel": 5,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/morrison-cou2-output-comparison-criteria",
      "rationale": "Quantitative output comparison performed using area validation metric (AVM) and U95 uncertainty bands per ASME V&V 20-2009. For the primary QoI (NIH), the model prediction falls within experimental U95 uncertainty bounds at all five operating points. Feature validation metrics applied to velocity profiles at three PIV planes: normalised RMS error 4.8–5.9%. Pressure-rise characteristic validated across full operating range with maximum deviation 3.1%. Formal validation report MCOC-2025-011 documents all comparison metrics, raw data, and statistical tests."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 5,
      "achievedLevel": 5,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/morrison-cou2-qoi-relevance-criteria",
      "rationale": "The primary QoI (normalised index of hemolysis, NIH) is directly linked to the regulatory decision criterion (absolute hemolysis level for Class II CPB device). Traceability matrix maps each model output to a specific regulatory requirement in 21 CFR 870.4360 and FDA guidance on blood-contacting devices. Secondary QoIs (velocity field, wall shear stress, turbulent dissipation rate) are mechanistically linked to hemolysis through the power-law damage accumulation model. Clinical relevance confirmed by haematology subject-matter expert review (SME sign-off MCSME-2025-002)."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 5,
      "achievedLevel": 5,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/morrison-cou2-validation-relevance-criteria",
      "rationale": "Validation activities were conducted using the identical FDA generic centrifugal blood pump geometry, the same operating range (2.5–6.0 L/min, 3000–4500 RPM), and clinically representative blood analog fluids. Geometric similarity verified by CMM inspection of test article (all critical dimensions within ±0.05 mm of CAD nominal). Fluid properties matched to ISO 10993-4 requirements. Validation domain covers the full COU operating envelope; no extrapolation beyond validated range is required for the intended regulatory submission."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 5,
      "achievedLevel": 5,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/morrison-cou2-solver-error-criteria",
      "rationale": "Iterative convergence assessed by monitoring residuals (continuity, momentum, k, omega, hemolysis scalar) to below 1×10⁻⁶ and by tracking NIH and torque monitors to steady-state (variation < 0.01% over final 500 iterations). Round-off error estimated via double-precision arithmetic analysis: negligible relative to discretization error. Iterative error contribution to NIH uncertainty: < 0.05%. Solver settings (relaxation factors, scheme order, convergence criteria) documented in simulation plan MCSE-2025-004 and reproduced in all production runs."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 5,
      "achievedLevel": 5,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/morrison-cou2-use-error-criteria",
      "rationale": "Use error controls implemented at multiple levels: (1) simulation setup checklists reviewed by independent analyst prior to each run; (2) automated pre-processing scripts with range checks on boundary conditions, material properties, and solver settings; (3) post-processing scripts with sanity checks (mass conservation < 0.01%, energy balance < 0.5%); (4) independent peer review of simulation reports by a second qualified engineer. All checklist records and peer-review sign-offs archived in project document control system MCUE-2025-005. No use errors identified in production runs."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 5,
      "achievedLevel": 5,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/morrison-cou2-model-form-criteria",
      "rationale": "Model form uncertainty assessed through systematic comparison of three turbulence model closures (k-ω SST, realizable k-ε, RSM) and two hemolysis constitutive models (Giersiepen power-law, Zhang modified power-law). k-ω SST with Zhang hemolysis model selected based on best agreement with experimental data across all operating points (lowest AVM score). Model form uncertainty contribution to NIH: ±6.3% (95% CI), quantified via Bayesian model averaging over the two hemolysis model variants. Sensitivity of conclusions to model form choice documented in uncertainty budget MCMF-2025-006."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 5,
      "achievedLevel": 5,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/morrison-cou2-model-inputs-criteria",
      "rationale": "All 12 model inputs characterised with probability distributions derived from measurement data, literature, or expert elicitation. Input uncertainty propagated through the model using Monte Carlo sampling (N = 10,000 LHS samples). Sobol sensitivity analysis identifies hemolysis power-law exponent (α) and rotational speed as dominant contributors (combined S_T = 0.69). Input uncertainty contribution to NIH: ±9.1% (95% CI). All input distributions, sources, and propagation methodology documented in uncertainty quantification report MCMI-2025-008. Dataset: morrison-uq-sensitivity-dataset-v1."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
